<TITLE> UK consumer morale at lowest since March 2003: GfK </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Nov 30 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British consumer morale fell for a fifth month running in November to its lowest level since the start of the Iraq war in March 2003, as people's optimism over the economic outlook soured, a survey showed on Friday. Research group GfK NOP's consumer confidence barometer fell to -10 in November from -8 the previous month. Analysts had forecast a more modest deterioration to -9. The decline suggests tougher credit conditions and higher living costs are taking their toll. Shoppers were more reluctant to make major purchases than at any time since the end of 1995, something that may worry retailers in the run-up to the crucial Christmas trading period. "With petrol prices racing past one pound a litre, food prices on the increase and the prospect of higher mortgages resulting from the credit crunch, even the most optimistic seem to view their glass as half-empty," said Rachael Joy of the research group's consumer confidence team. There were marked falls in people's confidence in both their own financial situation and the economy over the coming year, suggesting recent financial market turbulence is feeding through to the real econo
